### What did you do?
```
public static async Task Main(string[] args)
{
  Environment.SetEnvironmentVariable("GRPC_VERBOSITY", "DEBUG");
  Environment.SetEnvironmentVariable("GRPC_TRACE", "all");
  using var logger = TextWriter.Synchronized(File.CreateText("test.txt"));
  GrpcEnvironment.SetLogger(new TextWriterLogger(logger));

  Channel channel = new Channel("dns://127.0.0.1:8010/test.my-company.com", ChannelCredentials.Insecure, new[]
  {
    new ChannelOption("grpc.lb_policy_name", "grpclb"),
    new ChannelOption("grpc.service_config", "{\"serviceConfig\":{\"load_balancing_config\":{ \"grpclb\": {} },\"waitForReady\":true}}"),
    new ChannelOption("grpc.dns_enable_srv_queries", 1)
  });

  var client = new Delay.DelayClient(channel);
  var reply = await client.TestDelayAsync(new DelayRequest{Ticks = DateTime.UtcNow.Ticks});
  Console.WriteLine("Ticks: " + reply.Ticks);
  reply = await client.TestDelayAsync(new DelayRequest{Ticks = DateTime.UtcNow.Ticks});
  Console.WriteLine("Ticks: " + reply.Ticks);

  await channel.ShutdownAsync();
  Console.WriteLine("Press any key to exit...");
  Console.ReadKey();
}
```

### What did you expect to see?
The first call being slightly slower than the second due to DNS resolution, load balancing and subchannel creation,

### What did you see instead?
There is a huge delay before the first request is even trying to contact the DNS server of around 10-35 seconds: [test.txt](https://github.com/grpc/grpc/files/5157697/test.txt)

### Anything else we should know about your project / environment?
Doing direct calls to a IPv4 target results in the expected small delay without big time gap. So it seems to be related to c-ares or grpclb. Can’t use native DNS resolver as I need the authority to use grpclb as there is no way to define a resolver in C# or target grpclb directly (see #11879, #13639, #16617, #19874).

This is an issue for us since 2017 and especially Android will become a big issue for as since there is neither support for the resolver nor for c-ares to abuse as our workaround. We will have a look at xDS in the future, but I still first need to get our code working again as the last releases seem to have broken our workaround.

